A068052.name: Start from 1, shift one left and sum mod 2 (bitwise-XOR) to get 3 (11 in binary), then shift two steps left and XOR to get 15 (1111 in binary), then three steps and XOR to get 119 (1110111 in binary), then four steps and so on.
formula: a(0) = 1; for n > 0, a(n) = a(n-1) XOR (2^n)*a(n-1), where XOR is bitwise-XOR (A003987).
A000120(a(n)) = A285103(n). [Number of ones in binary representation.]

A068053.name: Start with one 1 in the infinite vector of zeros, shift one right or left and sum mod 2 (bitwise-XOR) to get 11, then shift two steps and XOR to get 1111, then three steps and XOR to get 1110111, then four steps and so on.

A068065.name: Palindromes n for which there is a unique k such that n = k + reverse(k).

A068066.name: The sum or half the sum of n consecutive primes starting at a(n) is prime.

A068067.name: Number of integers m, 0 < m <= n, such that n divides m(m+1)/2.
formula: If n is even, a(n) = 2^(omega(n)-1) - 1; if n is odd, a(n) = 2^omega(n). Here omega(n) = A001221(n) is the number of distinct prime divisors of n.
A068068(n) - a(n) = 0 if n is odd, 1 if n is even.

A068068.name: Number of odd unitary divisors of n. d is a unitary divisor of n if d divides n and gcd(d,n/d)=1.
formula: a(n) = A034444(2n)/2. If n is even, a(n) = 2^(omega(n)-1); if n is odd, a(n) = 2^omega(n). Here omega(n) = A001221(n) is the number of distinct prime divisors of n.
Dirichlet g.f.: zeta^2(s)/ ( zeta(2*s)*(1+2^(-s)) ). Dirichlet convolution of A034444 and A154269. - _R. J. Mathar_, Apr 16 2011
Sum_{k=1..n} a(k) ~ 4*n*((log(n) + 2*gamma - 1 + log(2)/3) / Pi^2 - 12*zeta'(2) / Pi^4), where gamma is the Euler-Mascheroni constant A001620. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Sep 18 2020

A068069.name: a(n) = least k which is the start of n consecutive integers each with a different number, 1 through n, of distinct prime factors.
formula: Koninck, Friedlander, & Luca prove that a(n) > exp(2n + o(n)), but note that an earlier result of Erdős is "essentially equivalent". - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Feb 04 2013

A068070.name: Number of digits in 10^n-th Fibonacci number.
formula: Can be calculated easily using the fact that Fibonacci(n) is very close to GoldenRatio^n/(2*GoldenRatio-1) (cf. A000045). - Michael Taktikos, Aug 11 2004

A068071.name: Triangular numbers that remain triangular when the least significant digit is moved to the beginning.

A068072.name: Number of Pluperfect Digital Invariants base n.

A068073.name: Period 4 sequence [ 1, 2, 3, 2, ...].
formula: Moebius transform is length 4 sequence [2, 1, 0, -2]. - _Michael Somos_, Feb 13 2011
a(n) = a(-n) = a(n+4) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Apr 17 2015
2 * a(n) = A164356(n) unless n=0. - _Michael Somos_, Apr 17 2015

A068074.name: a(n) = Sum_{d|n} (-1)^d*2^omega(n/d) where omega(x) is the number of distinct prime factors in the factorization of x.
formula: Asymptotic formula: Sum_{k=1..n} a(k)/k = -C*log(n)^2 with C = 3*log(2)/Pi^2.
a(n) = -tau(n^2) for odd n and 2*tau(n^2/4) - tau(n^2) for even n. b(n) = abs(a(n)) is multiplicative with b(2^e) = abs(2*e-3) and b(p^e) = 2*e+1 for an odd prime p. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Apr 25 2002
a(n) = if n odd then -A048691(n) else 2*A048691(n/2) - A048691(n). - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Jul 12 2012

A068075.name: Lesser of a primitive pair such that n and its 10's complement are simultaneously square.

A068076.name: Number of positive integers < n with the same number of 1's in their binary expansions as n.

A068078.name: Numbers n such that (sigma(n)+sigma(n+1))/n is an integer.

A068079.name: Decimal expansion of 355 / 113.
formula: a(n) = a(n - 112) for n > 113. - _Jeppe Stig Nielsen_, Dec 14 2019

A068080.name: Integers n such that n + phi(n) is a prime.

A068081.name: Numbers n such that n + phi(n) and n - phi(n) are prime.

A068082.name: a(1) = 1, a(n) = smallest triangular number of the form k*a(n-1) + 1 for some positive integer k.
formula: Conjectures confirmed by _Robert Israel_, Jun 05 2018 (see link).

A068083.name: a(1) = 1, a(n) is the smallest Fibonacci number of the form k*a(n-1) + 1 with k>0.

A068084.name: Smallest triangular number which is a multiple (>1) of the n-th triangular number.

A068085.name: Numbers k such that k and 10*k are both triangular numbers.
formula: a(n) = b(n)*(b(n)+1)/2 where b(n) is A341893(n). (End)

A068088.name: n-3, n-2, n-1, n+1, n+2 and n+3 are squarefree.

A068090.name: Numbers n which divide the right concatenation of the first n even numbers.

A068091.name: Number of board-pair-pile hexagonal polyominoes with n cells.

A068092.name: Index of smallest triangular number with n digits.
formula: a(n) = b where b = floor(sqrt(2*10^(n-1))) and if b(b+1)/2 < 10^(n-1), then b = b+1.

A068093.name: Smallest n-digit triangular number.
formula: Triangular number with index given by A068092.

A068094.name: Number of n-digit triangular numbers.
formula: Differences of successive terms of A068092.

A068095.name: All primes dividing each term are Fibonacci numbers.

A068096.name: a(n) = F(L(n)) where F(n) = n-th Fibonacci number and L(n) = n-th Lucas number.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=1..F(n-1)+1} binomial(F(n-1), k-1)*F(F(n)+k-1), where F(n) is A000045. - _Tony Foster III_, Sep 03 2018

A068097.name: a(1) = 1; a(n+1) = smallest triangular numbers starting with a(n).

A068098.name: a(n) = Lucas(Fibonacci(n)).
formula: For n > 2, a(n) = round{Phi^Fibonacci(n-1)}. - _Gerald McGarvey_, Sep 19 2004

A068099.name: a(1) = 1; a(n+1) = n! sum{k|n} a(k)/k where sum is over positive divisors k of n.

A068100.name: a(1) = 1; a(n+1) = n!*Sum_{k|n} a(k)/k!.
formula: E.g.f.: Sum_{n>=1} a(n) * x^n / (n!*(1 - x^n)) = Sum_{n>=1} a(n+1) * x^n / n!. - _Paul D. Hanna_, Sep 04 2014
E.g.f. A(x) satisfies: d/dx A(x) = 1 + A(x) + A(x^2) + A(x^3) + ... - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, May 10 2019

A068101.name: a(n) = Sum_{k|n, k<=sqrt(n)} mu(k) where mu(k) is the Moebius function and the sum is over the positive divisors k of n with k <= sqrt(n).
formula: G.f.: Sum_{k>=1} mu(k)*x^(k^2)/(1 - x^k). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Jan 03 2017

A068102.name: a(n) = n! * 2^n * Sum_{i=1..n} 1/(i*2^i).
formula: a(n+1) = 2*(n+1)*a(n) + n!, a(0)=0. - _Jaume Oliver Lafont_, Sep 15 2009

The sequence b(n) = 2^n*n! = A000165(n) also satisfies the above second-order recurrence of Kotesovec. This leads to the generalized continued fraction expansion limit {n -> inf} a(n)/b(n) = log(2) = 1/(2 - 2/(5 - 8/(8 - 18/(11 - ... - 2*(n - 1)^2/((3*n - 1) - ... ))))). - _Peter Bala_, Feb 18 2015

A068103.name: Smallest prime starting with at least n 2s.

A068106.name: Euler's difference table: triangle read by rows, formed by starting with factorial numbers (A000142) and repeatedly taking differences. T(n,n) = n!, T(n,k) = T(n,k+1) - T(n-1,k).
formula: T(n, k) = Sum_{j>= 0} (-1)^j*binomial(n-k, j)*(n-j)!. - _Philippe Deléham_, May 29 2005
T(n,k) = Sum_{j=0..k} d(n-j)*binomial(k, j), where d(i) = A000166(i) are the derangement numbers.

A068179.name: Product_{i=1..3} (i+x) / Product_(i=1..3} (i-x) = Sum_{n>=0} (a(n)/b(n))*x^n.
formula: General case: lim_{m-->+oo} a_n(m)/b_n(m) = A002378(n) where
Product_{i=1..d} (x+i)/Product_{i=1..d} (i-x) = Sum_{n>=0} (a_d(n)/b_d(n))*x^n) = ((-1)^d) * (1 + Sum_{j>=1} (Sum_{k=1..d} ((-1)^k/k^j) * binomial(2*k,k) * binomial(d+k,2*k)) * x^j). (End)

Also the number of combinatorially distinct identifications of pairs of edges of a polygone P having 12g-6 sides leading to a compact oriented genus g surface containing the boundary of P as a 3-regular graph.
formula: Reference gives a formula. Another formula can be derived by use of characters of the symmetric groups.

A068185.name: Number of ways writing n^n as a product of decimal digits of some other number which has no digits equal to 1.

A068187.name: a(n) is the smallest number such that the product of its decimal digits equals n^n, or 0 if no solutions exist.

A068189.name: Smallest positive number whose product of digits equals n, or a(n)=0 if no such number exists, i.e. when n has a prime divisor greater than 7.

A068461.name: Factorial, or factoradic, expansion of log(11) = Sum_{n>=1} a(n)/n!, with a(n) as large as possible.

A068462.name: Factorial expansion of the cube root of 2: 2^(1/3) = Sum_{n>0} a(n)/n!.

A068463.name: Factorial expansion of Gamma(3/4) = Sum_{n>=1} a(n)/n! where Gamma is Euler's gamma function.

A068464.name: Factorial expansion of Gamma(1/4) = Sum_{n>=1} a(n)/n! with largest possible a(n), and Gamma = Euler's gamma function.
formula: a(n) = floor(n!*Gamma(1/4)) - n*floor((n-1)!*Gamma(1/4)), for n > 1. - _M. F. Hasler_, Nov 26 2018

A068465.name: Decimal expansion of Gamma(3/4).
formula: This number * A068466 = sqrt(2)*Pi = A063448. - _R. J. Mathar_, Jun 18 2006
Equals Integral_{x>=0} x^(-1/4)*exp(-x) dx. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Nov 12 2020
Equals (Pi/2)^(1/4) * sqrt(AGM(1,sqrt(2))) = sqrt(A069998 * A053004). - _Amiram Eldar_, Jun 12 2021

A068466.name: Decimal expansion of Gamma(1/4).
formula: Equals sqrt(2*sqrt(2*Pi^3)*G), where G is Gauss's constant (A014549).

A068467.name: Decimal expansion of (1/4)! = Gamma(5/4).
formula: 2^(3/4)*(2/e^(16*Pi) + 1)* Pi^(3/4)/(2^(13/16)/(sqrt(2) - 1)^(1/4) + 2^(1/4) + 1) is a very good approximation (~88 digits) which becomes exact if you replace (2/e^(16*Pi) + 1) by EllipticTheta[3,0,exp(-(16*Pi))]. [R. W. Gosper, Posting to Math Fun Mailing List, Dec 27 2011.]
Also equals integral_{0..oo} exp(-x^4) dx. - _Jean-François Alcover_, Mar 29 2013

A068471.name: Number of n X n binary matrices with each 1 having at most 2 adjacent 1's.

A068472.name: Number of n X n binary matrices with every 1 having at most 3 adjacent 1's.

A068477.name: a(n) is the digital sum of 1^n + 2^n + ... + n^n.

A068484.name: Numbers n such that n divides phi(n)^2 + sigma(n)^2.

A068485.name: One-sixtieth of the even leg of Pythagorean triangles whose other sides are both primes (other than 3, 5 or 13).

A068486.name: Smallest prime equal to n^2 + m^2 with n >= m.

A068487.name: Smallest prime equal to n^2 + m^2 with n<m.

A068488.name: m for which p(m) is the least prime dividing #p(n) + 1, i.e., primorial n-th prime augmented by 1 (A005234).

A068489.name: m for which p(m) is the least prime dividing #p(n) - 1, i.e., one less than primorial n-th prime (A057588).

A068490.name: In the Ana sequence, use (the ungrammatical) "a n" instead of "an n" in describing n's. That is, begin with the letter "a". Generate the next term by using the indefinite article as appropriate, but using "a n" instead of "an n". E.g., "an a", then "an a, a n, an a" etc. Assign a=1, n=2.

A068491.name: Expansion of Molien series for a certain 4-D group of order 96.

A068492.name: Primes that remain prime after each digit is replaced by its square.

A068493.name: Primes which are concatenations of squares.

A068494.name: a(n) = n mod phi(n).
formula: b^(n - a(n)) == 1 (mod n) for every b coprime to n. - _Thomas Ordowski_, Jun 30 2017

A068495.name: Composite n such that n reduced mod(phi(n)) = sigma(n) reduced mod(n).

A068497.name: Primes p such that 2*p+1 and 2*p-1 are composites.

A068498.name: Fibonacci numbers whose sum of decimal digits is greater than its index.

A068499.name: Numbers m such that m! reduced modulo (m+1) is not zero.
formula: For n <> 3, all terms are one less prime. - _Zak Seidov_, Aug 22 2012
a(n) = Integer part of A078456(n+1)/A078456(n). - _Eric Desbiaux_, May 07 2013

A068500.name: Sequence of Fibonacci numbers whose sum of decimal digits sets a new record.

A068501.name: Values m such that the consecutive pair parameters(m,m+1) generate Pythagorean triples whose odd terms are both prime.

A068505.name: Decimal representation of n interpreted in base b+1, where b=A054055(n) is the largest digit in decimal representation of n.

A068506.name: Least highly composite number whose prime decomposition starts with 2^n.

A068507.name: Highly composite numbers sandwiched between twin primes.

A068509.name: a(n) = maximum length of a subset in {1,..,n} whose integers have pairwise LCM not exceeding n.
formula: (3*sqrt(n))/(2*sqrt(2)) - 2 < a(n) <= 1.638*sqrt(n). - P. Erdos and S. L. G. Choi

A068512.name: Numerators of arithmetic derivative of n/2: A003415(n)/2 - n/4; denominators: A010685.

A068513.name: a(0) = 15; for n > 0, a(n) is the smallest triangular number which is a (proper) multiple of a(n-1).

A068514.name: Numbers of the form (2i)! (2j)! / i! j! (i + j)!.

A068515.name: A measure of how close the square root of 2 is to rational numbers.

A068516.name: Number of squares (of another matrix) in the group GL(2,Z_n) described in sequence A000252.

A068517.name: a(2n) = concatenation of 4n+1 and 4n+2, a(2n+1) = concatenation of the two most nearly equal numbers whose product is a(2n).

A068518.name: The sequence S(n,-3,1,1), where S(r,k,t,q) is defined by Sum(0<=j<=r){combin(r+q,j)^t*B(j,k)} and B(j,k) is the j-th k-poly-Bernoulli number.

A068519.name: If n is prime then a(n) = n, else a(n) = prime(n).

A068520.name: Numbers n which can be transformed into a true arithmetic statement by inserting zero or more parentheses and elementary arithmetic operators ((, ), +, -, *, /) and one equality sign (=) as the rightmost insertion into the decimal representation of n.

A068522.name: In base 10 notation replace digits of n with their squared values (Version 2).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{i=0..g} d(i)*d(i)*10^i, where n = Sum_{d=0..9} d(i)*10^i is the decimal expansion of n.

A068524.name: a(1) = 2; for n > 1, a(n) = largest prime not exceeding a(1) + ... + a(n-1).

A068525.name: Smallest k-almost prime between twin primes (for k >= 2).

A068526.name: Numbers n such that prime(n+1)-prime(n) = tau(n) = A000005(n).

A068527.name: Difference between smallest square >= n and n.
formula: G.f.: (-x^2 + (x-x^2)*Sum_{m>=1} (1+2*m)*x^(m^2))/(1-x)^2. This sum is related to Jacobi Theta functions. - _Robert Israel_, Nov 17 2014

A068528.name: Let N(2k) denote the numerator of B(2k), the 2k-th Bernoulli number, and D(2k) the denominator; sequence gives values of k such that gcd(N(2k),D(2k-2))=5.

A068535.name: Numbers k such that 2^k mod k = 2^k mod k^2.

A068536.name: Numbers n such that n^2 + (reversal of n)^2 is a perfect square. Ignore leading 0's.

A068537.name: Numbers which can be written as the sum of 2 like powers (x^n + y^n; n>1 & x,y>0).

A068539.name: Number of quinternary cubefree words of length n.

A068541.name: Let sqrt(2) = 1.d(1)d(2)d(3)... = 1.0110101000001... be the expansion of sqrt(2) in base 2; sequence gives values of j such that j/2 = Sum_{k=1..j} d(k).

A068542.name: Period of the fraction 1/3^n.
formula: a(n) = floor(10^(3^max(n-2,0)+L(3^n))/3^n) where L(m) = floor(log10(m)). - _M. F. Hasler_, Apr 23 2021

A068543.name: Numbers n such that abs(prime(n)-n*tau(n)) < sqrt(n).

A068548.name: Coefficients of (-x^(2n-6)) in Chebyshev polynomial of degree 2n.

A068551.name: a(n) = 4^n - binomial(2*n,n).
formula: G.f.: 1/(1 - 4*x) - 1/sqrt(1 - 4*x) = C(x)*2*x/(1 - 4*x) where C(x) = g.f. for Catalan numbers A000108.
a(n) = Sum{k >= 1} binomial(2*m-2*k, m-k) * binomial(2*k, k).

A068555.name: Triangle read by rows in which row n contains (2i)!*(2j)!/(i!*j!*(i+j)!) for i+j=n, i=0..n.
formula: The square array defined by f := (a, b)->add(binomial(2*a, k)*binomial(2*b, a+b-k)*(-1)^(a+b-k), k=0..2*a); and read by antidiagonals gives a signed version. See Sprugnoli, 3.38.
T(n,0) = A000984(n), T(n,k) = 4*T(n-1,k-1) - T(n,k-1) for k = 1..n. - _Philippe Deléham_, Mar 10 2014

A068556.name: From numerators in expansion of tan(arcsinh(x)) - sin(arctanh(x)).

A068557.name: From denominators in expansion of tan(arcsinh(x)) - sin(arctanh(x)).

A068558.name: Decimal expansion of the smallest solution >0 to cos(x)=cos(x^2).

A068559.name: Numbers m such that phi(m) = tau(m)^3.

A068560.name: Numbers k such that phi(k) = tau(k)^2.

A068561.name: Numerators of coefficients in (1+x)^(1/3)-(1-x)^(1/3) power series.

A068562.name: Denominators of coefficients in (1+x)^(1/3)-(1-x)^(1/3) power series.

A068567.name: Numbers k such that gpf(k) < k/gpf(k) and gpf(k/gpf(k)) < gpf(k), where gpf(n) is the greatest prime factor of n, A006530.

A068568.name: Let S = a subset of {n,n+1,n+2,..,n+m}, number of parts of S is more than 1. a(n) = smallest number m such that the product of parts of S is a square.

A068569.name: Positive numbers that are not the ratio of any n/(# of letters to express n in English).

A068570.name: Numbers divisible by the number of letters to express them in English.

A068571.name: Number of happy numbers <= 10^n.
formula: h(n,x) = h(n-1,x-0^2) + h(n-1,x-1^2) + ... + h(n-1,x-9^2) where h() is the number of numbers of length n whose sum of the squares of their digits is x.
a(n) is the sum of all h(n, 0 < x <= 81*n), where x is a happy number, plus 1 for 10^n. (End)

A068572.name: Numbers n such that sigma(n) = product of the squares of the decimal digits of n.

A068573.name: a(n) is the smallest positive integer such that no term in S={a(1),...,a(n)}, n>=3, divides the sum of any two other distinct terms of S, after first initializing the sequence with a(1)=3 and a(2)=4.

A068574.name: As strings, n is a substring of Fibonacci(n).

A068575.name: Numbers n such that, as strings, n is a substring of prime(n).

A068576.name: Numbers k such that Sum_{j=1..k} mu(j)^2 = floor(6*k/Pi^2).

A068577.name: Numbers n such that tau(n)^2 > phi(n).

A068578.name: Numbers k such that tau(k)*sigma(k) > k*phi(k).

A068579.name: Let phi_m(x) = phi(phi(...(phi(x))...)) m times; sequence gives values of k such that phi_3(k) = tau(k).

A068580.name: Let phi_m(x) = phi(phi(...(phi(x))...)) m times; sequence gives values of k such that phi_2(k) = tau(k).

A068581.name: Let phi_m(x) = phi(phi(...(phi(x))...)) m times; sequence gives values of k such that phi_4(k) = tau(k).

A068582.name: Let phi_m(x) = phi(phi(...(phi(x))...)) m times; sequence gives values of k such that phi_5(k) = tau(k).

A068583.name: p and q are primes. p^x - q^y = 2^h. ( p != q, h=>0, x>1, y>1 ) : sequence gives p^x arranged in increasing order.

A068584.name: Numbers k such that the denominator of (Sum_{j=1..k} 1/j)^2 equals the denominator of Sum_{j=1..k} 1/j^2.
formula: Numbers k such that A002805(k)^2 = A007407(k).

A068585.name: Numbers k such that the denominator of (Sum_{j=1..k} 1/j)^3 equals the denominator of Sum_{j=1..k} 1/j^3.
formula: Numbers k such that A002805(k)^3 = A007409(k).

A068587.name: Multiplicative 3-wave sequence starting with 1,2,3.
formula: a(n)=a(n-1)*a(n-2) if n is odd, a(n)=a(n-1)*a(n-4) if n is even.

A068588.name: Treated as strings, n and its reversal are substrings of 2^n.

A068590.name: Number of different Euler multigraphs with n edges, loops allowed.

A068592.name: Number of different Euler multigraphs with n edges, loops forbidden.

A068594.name: Factorable subsets: the number of subsets S of {1,2,...,n} that can be expressed in the form S=A*B, where B is defined to be the set {a(i)*b(j)| a(i) in A, b(j) in B}.

A068595.name: Number of functions from {1,2,...,n} to {1,2,...,n} such that the sum of the function values is 0 mod 3.

A068596.name: Number of 4-ary Lyndon words whose trace and subtrace are both 0 mod 4.

A068597.name: Barriers for bigomega(n): numbers n such that, for all m < n, m + bigomega(m) <= n.

A068598.name: Number of maximal sets of partitions of n with property that all parts in all partitions in the set are distinct.

A068600.name: Number of n-uniform tilings having n different arrangements of polygons about their vertices.

A068601.name: a(n) = n^3 - 1.
formula: Partial sums of A003215, hex (or centered hexagonal) numbers: 3*n(n+1)+1. - _Jonathan Vos Post_, Mar 16 2006
a(n) = Sum_{i=1..n-1} (i+1)^3 - i^3. - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Jul 23 2014

A068602.name: Number of functions f:{0,1,2,...,n} -> {0,1,2,...,n} that satisfy f(0)=0 and f(n)=0, with f nowhere concave upward.

A068603.name: Numbers n such that prime(n)+prime(2n)+prime(3n) is prime.

A068604.name: Number of distinct coefficients in expansion related to enumeration of permutations of length n by length of longest subsequence.

A068605.name: Number of functions from [1,2,...,n] to [1,2,...,n] such that the image contains exactly two elements.

A068606.name: Square table by antidiagonals of T(n,k)=n*k*(n+k+1).

A068608.name: Path of a knight's tour on an infinite chessboard.

A068609.name: Path of a knight's tour on an infinite chessboard.

A068610.name: Path of a knight's tour on an infinite chessboard.

A068611.name: Path of a knight's tour on an infinite chessboard.

A068612.name: Path of a knight's tour on an infinite chessboard.

A068613.name: Path of a knight's tour on an infinite chessboard.

A068614.name: Path of a knight's tour on an infinite chessboard.

A068615.name: Path of a knight's tour on an infinite chessboard.

A068616.name: Starting from a(1)=7, each subsequent term is the minimal square obtained by inserting at least one digit into the previous term.

A068617.name: Starting from a(1)=8, each subsequent term is the minimal square obtained by inserting at least one digit in the previous term.

A068618.name: a(1) = 1; a(n+1) = smallest triangular number > a(n) formed by adding at least one digit to a(n).

A068619.name: a(1) = 3; a(n+1) = smallest triangular number formed by inserting one or more digits into a(n).

A068620.name: Number of strings over Z_4 of length n with trace 0 and subtrace 0.
formula: a(n; t, s) = a(n-1; t, s) + a(n-1; t+3, s+3t+1) + a(n-1; t+2, s+2t) + a(n-1; t+1, s+t+1) where t is the trace and s is the subtrace.

A068621.name: a(1) = 7; a(n+1) = smallest triangular number > a(n) formed by adding at least one digit to a(n).

A068622.name: a(1) = 5; a(n+1) = smallest triangular number > a(n) formed by adding at least one digit to a(n).

A068623.name: a(1) = 8; a(n+1) = smallest triangular number > a(n) formed by adding at least one digit to a(n).

A068624.name: a(1) = 9; a(n+1) = smallest triangular number > a(n) formed by adding at least one digit to a(n).

A068625.name: Reduced root factorial of n: product of the smallest integer root of numbers from 1 to n.

A068627.name: a(0) = 0, a(n) = a(n-1) + n if n does not divide a(n-1). a(n) = a(n-1) - n if n divides a(n-1). a(n) = n if a(n-1) = 0.

A068629.name: a(1) = 1. a(n) = n*a(n-1) if gcd(n,a(n-1)) = 1, a(n-1)/n if n divides a(n-1), otherwise a(n) = a(n-1).

A068630.name: a(0)=0; a(n) = n + a(n-1) if gcd(n,a(n-1)) = 1 or a(n-1) = 0; a(n) = a(n-1) - n if n divides a(n-1), otherwise a(n) = a(n-1).

A068631.name: a(1) = 4; a(n) = smallest composite number different from the previous ones such that the sum of all the terms is a composite number.

A068632.name: a(1) = 2; a(n+1) = smallest composite number not in the sequence such that the sum of all the terms is prime.

A068633.name: a(1) = 11 by convention; for n > 1, if n = p^a*q^b... then a(n) = concatenate(p,a,q,b,...).

A068634.name: a(n) = lcm(n, R(n)), where R(n) (A004086) = digit reversal of n.

A068635.name: Smaller of the first twin pair to yield a twin pair chain of length n.

A068636.name: a(n) = Min(n, R(n)), where R(n) (A004086) = digit reversal of n.

A068637.name: a(n) = Max(n, R(n)), where R(n) (A004086) = digit reversal of n.

A068638.name: a(1) = 1, a(n) = smallest distinct composite number such that a(n) + a(k) is a composite number for all k = 1 to n.

A068639.name: a(0) = 0, a(n) = a(n-1) + (-1)^p(n) for n >= 1, where p(n) = highest power of 2 dividing n.
formula: a(n)=(n+2*A065359(n))/3; a(n) is asymptotic to n/3. - _Benoit Cloitre_, Oct 04 2003

A068640.name: Define f(n) = 2n+1, a(n) = largest prime of the form f(f(f(...(n))). If no such prime exists then a(n) = 0.

A068641.name: Smallest n-digit palindromic triangular number, or 0 if no such number exists.

A068642.name: Index of the smallest n-digit palindromic triangular number, or 0 if no such number exists.

A068643.name: Largest n-digit palindromic triangular number, or 0 if no such number exists.

A068644.name: Index of the largest n-digit palindromic triangular number, or 0 if no such number exists.

A068645.name: Primes in which a string of 3's is sandwiched between two 1's.

A068646.name: Primes in which a string of 5's is sandwiched between two 1's.

A068647.name: Primes in which a string of 6's is sandwiched between two 1's.

A068648.name: Primes in which a string of 8's is sandwiched between two 1's.

A068649.name: Primes in which a string of 9's is sandwiched between two 1's.

A068650.name: Primes in which a string of 1's is sandwiched between two 3's.

A068651.name: Primes in which a string of 2's is sandwiched between two 9's.

A068652.name: Numbers such that every cyclic permutation is a prime.

A068653.name: Composite numbers such that every cyclic shift (other than the number itself) gives a prime.

A068654.name: Prime numbers such that every cyclic permutation (other than the number itself) is composite.

A068655.name: Primes which are a concatenation of at least two consecutive primes.

A068657.name: Successive left concatenation of floor(k/2) beginning with n until we reach 1.

A068659.name: Primes formed from the concatenation of n, n-1 and n for some n > 0.

A068660.name: Primes formed from the concatenation of n, n+1 and n for some n.

A068661.name: Let N = 123456789101112131415... the concatenation of natural numbers; partition this number into minimal strings of noncomposite numbers, i.e., a(1) = 1 and a(2) onwards are primes.

A068662.name: Let N = 1357911131517192123252729... the concatenation of odd numbers; partition this number into minimal strings of primes.

A068663.name: Let N = 23571113171923293137... the concatenation of primes; partition this number into minimal strings of composite numbers.

A068664.name: a(1) = 1, a(n) = smallest palindromic multiple of a(n-1).

A068665.name: a(1) = 3; a(n) = smallest palindromic multiple of a(n-1).

A068666.name: a(1) = 5; a(n) = smallest palindromic multiple of a(n-1).

A068667.name: a(1) = 7; a(n) = smallest palindromic multiple of a(n-1).

A068668.name: a(1) = 9; a(n) = smallest palindromic multiple of a(n-1).

A068669.name: Noncomposite numbers in which every substring is noncomposite.

A068670.name: Number of digits in the concatenation of first n primes.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{i=1..n} ceiling(log_10(1 + prime(i))). - _Daniel Forgues_, Apr 02 2014

A068671.name: Define f(n,k) = floor[n/k] and a(n) = right concatenation of f(n,k) for k = 1 to int[(n+1)/2] or until one arrives at a 1.

A068673.name: Numbers which yield primes when a 1 is prefixed or appended.

A068674.name: Numbers which yield primes when a 3 is prefixed or appended.

A068675.name: Numbers n such that a prime can be obtained by inserting a 1 before, somewhere inside of, or after n.

A068676.name: Primes formed by the concatenation 1, n, n^2, n, 1.

A068677.name: Numbers that yield a prime when a 7 is prefixed or suffixed to them.

A068678.name: Numbers that yield a prime when a 9 is prefixed or suffixed to them.

A068679.name: Numbers which yield a prime whenever a 1 is inserted anywhere in them (including at the beginning or end).

A068680.name: Primes formed by the concatenation n, n+2, n.

A068681.name: Primes formed by the concatenation n, n-2, n.

A068682.name: Numbers n such that the concatenations n, n-2, n and n, n+2, n are primes.

A068683.name: Primes formed by the concatenation p,q,p where p and q are successive primes and p>q.

A068684.name: Primes obtained as a concatenation p,q,p where p and q are successive primes and p<q.

A068685.name: Primes which are a sandwich of numbers using at most one digit between two 1's.

A068686.name: Let p = abc..k be a prime in base 10. Define mirror(p) = abc...k...cba. Sequence gives primes of the form mirror(p) for some p.

A068687.name: Primes which are a sandwich of numbers made of only one digit between two 3's.

A068688.name: Primes which are a sandwich of numbers made of only one digit between two 7's.

A068689.name: Primes which are a sandwich of numbers made of only one decimal digit between two 9's.

A068690.name: Primes such that all digits (except perhaps the least significant digit) are even.

A068691.name: Smallest n-digit prime with all even digits except the least significant digit.

A068692.name: Largest n-digit prime with all even digits except for the least significant digit.

A068693.name: Smallest n-digit prime with all odd digits.

A068694.name: Largest n-digit prime with all odd digits.

A068695.name: Smallest number (not beginning with 0) that yields a prime when placed on the right of n.

A068696.name: Number of primes that are a concatenation nk of n and k for values of k from 1 to n.

A068697.name: Smallest prime which is a concatenation of n consecutive odd numbers. If no such prime exists then 0.

A068698.name: Smallest primes in the reverse concatenation of n odd numbers.

A068700.name: The concatenation of n with n-1 and n with n+1 both yield primes (twin primes).

A068701.name: Primes in the concatenation n^2, n and 1.

A068702.name: Numbers n such that concatenation n^2, n and 1 is a prime.

A068703.name: Primes in the concatenation n,n+1, n+2, n+1, n.

A068704.name: a(n) = smallest prime obtained as the concatenation of n^k, n^(k-1), n^(k-2), ..., n^2, n, 1 for some k >= 1; or 0 if no such prime exists.

A068706.name: Primes obtained as a right concatenation of more than one consecutive even numbers and 1.

A068707.name: Smallest prime obtained as a right concatenation of n consecutive even numbers and 1.

A068708.name: Squares whose digits can be arranged in increasing cyclic order - to form a substring of 123456789012345678901234567890...

A068710.name: Primes whose digits can be arranged in increasing cyclic order - to form a substring of 123456789012345678901234567890...

A068711.name: S(n; 0,1) = S(n; 2,3) where S(n; t,s) is the number of length n 4-ary strings whose digits sum to t mod 4 and whose sum of products of all pairs of digits sum to s mod 4.

A068713.name: Values of n for which 10*2^n + 3 is a prime (giving terms of A068712).

A068907.name: Number of partitions of n modulo 3.
formula: a(n) = Pm(n,1) with Pm(n,k) = if k<n then (Pm(n-k,k) + Pm(n,k+1)) mod 3 else 0^(n*(k-n)). - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Jun 09 2009

A068908.name: Number of partitions of n modulo 5.
formula: a(n) = Pm(n,1) with Pm(n,k) = if k<n then (Pm(n-k,k) + Pm(n,k+1)) mod 5 else 0^(n*(k-n)). [From _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Jun 09 2009]

A068909.name: Number of partitions of n modulo 7.
formula: a(n) = Pm(n,1) with Pm(n,k) = if k<n then (Pm(n-k,k) + Pm(n,k+1)) mod 7 else 0^(n*(k-n)). [From _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Jun 09 2009]

A068910.name: a(n) is the unique k such that palindrome A068065(n) = k + reverse(k).

A068911.name: Number of n step walks (each step +/-1 starting from 0) which are never more than 2 or less than -2.
formula: For n > 2, indexing from 0, a(n) = a(n-1)+a(n-2) if n is odd, a(n-1)+a(n-2)+a(n-3) if n is even. - _Alec Jones_, Feb 25 2016
a(n) = 2*a(n-1) if n is even, a(n-1)+a(n-2) if n is odd. - _Vincenzo Librandi_, Feb 26 2016

A068912.name: Number of n step walks (each step +/-1 starting from 0) which are never more than 3 or less than -3.
formula: With the standard procedure to obtain an explicit formula for a(n) for a linear recurrence and r1=2-sqrt(2) and r2=2+sqrt(2) we get
We have -1<a1(n)<0 for all n, so a(n)= floor(a2(n)). (End)

A068913.name: Square array read by antidiagonals of number of k step walks (each step +-1 starting from 0) which are never more than n or less than -n.
formula: Starting with T(n, 0) = 1, if (k-n) is negative or even then T(n, k) = 2*T(n, k-1), otherwise T(n, k) = 2*T(n, k-1)-A061897(n-1, (k-n-1)/2). So for n>=k, T(n, k) = 2^k.

A068914.name: Square array read by antidiagonals of number of k step walks (each step +-1 starting from 0) which are never more than n or less than 0.
formula: An explicit expression for the (n,k)-entry of the square array can be found in the R. Kemp reference (Theorem 2 on p. 159). - _Emeric Deutsch_, Jun 16 2011
The g.f. of column k is (1 + v^2)*(1 - v^(k+1))/((1 - v)*(1 + v^(k+2))), where v = (1 - sqrt(1-4*z^2))/(2*z) (see p. 159 of the R. Kemp reference). - _Emeric Deutsch_, Jun 16 2011

A068915.name: a(n) = n if n<2; a(n) = |a(n/2)-a(n/2-1)| if n is even, and a(n) = a((n-1)/2) + a((n-1)/2+1) if n is odd.

A068916.name: Smallest positive integer that is equal to the sum of the n-th powers of its prime factors (counted with multiplicity).

A068917.name: Numerators of coefficients in 1/sin(x) - 1/sinh(x) power series.

A068918.name: Denominators of coefficients in 1/sin(x) - 1/sinh(x) power series.

A068920.name: Table of t(r,s) by diagonals, where t(r,s) is the number of ways to tile an r X s room with 1x2 Tatami mats. At most 3 Tatami mats may meet at a point.

A068921.name: Number of ways to tile a 2 X n room with 1x2 Tatami mats. At most 3 Tatami mats may meet at a point.
formula: G.f.: Q(0)*( 1+x^2 )/2, where Q(k) = 1 + 1/(1 - x*(4*k+1 + x^2)/( x*(4*k+3 + x^2) + 1/Q(k+1) )); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Sep 08 2013

A068922.name: Number of ways to tile a 3 X 2n room with 1 X 2 Tatami mats. At most 3 Tatami mats may meet at a point.
formula: For n >= 2, a(n) = 2*F(n+1), where F(n)=A000045(n) is the n-th Fibonacci number.
G.f.: x*(x^2-x-3) / (x^2+x-1). - Maksym Voznyy (voznyy(AT)mail.ru), Aug 11 2009; checked and corrected by _R. J. Mathar_, Sep 16 2009

A068923.name: Number of ways to tile a 4 X n room with 1x2 Tatami mats. At most 3 Tatami mats may meet at a point.

A068924.name: Number of ways to tile a 5 X 2n room with 1x2 Tatami mats. At most 3 Tatami mats may meet at a point.
formula: G.f.: x*(-6+x^4+7*x^3+4*x^2-3*x)/(-1+x^3+x^2). [Maksym Voznyy (voznyy(AT)mail.ru), Aug 11 2009; checked and corrected by _R. J. Mathar_, Sep 16 2009]

A068925.name: Number of ways to tile a 6 X n room with 1x2 Tatami mats. At most 3 Tatami mats may meet at a point.

A068926.name: Table of ti(r,s) by diagonals, where ti(r,s) is the number of incongruent ways to tile an r X s room with 1x2 Tatami mats. At most 3 Tatami mats may meet at a point.

A068927.name: Number of incongruent ways to tile a 2 X n room with 1x2 Tatami mats. At most 3 Tatami mats may meet at a point.

A068928.name: Number of incongruent ways to tile a 3 X 2n room with 1x2 Tatami mats. At most 3 Tatami mats may meet at a point.

A068929.name: Number of incongruent ways to tile a 4 X n room with 1x2 Tatami mats. At most 3 Tatami mats may meet at a point.

A068930.name: Number of incongruent ways to tile a 5 X 2n room with 1x2 Tatami mats. At most 3 Tatami mats may meet at a point.
formula: a(n) = sum(A102541(n-k-2, n-2*k-4), k=0..floor((n-4)/2)), n >= 4. - _Johannes W. Meijer_, Aug 24 2013

A068931.name: Number of incongruent ways to tile a 6 X n room with 1x2 Tatami mats. At most 3 Tatami mats may meet at a point.

A068932.name: Number of disconnected regular graphs with n nodes.

A068933.name: Triangular array D(n, r) = number of disconnected r-regular graphs with n nodes, 0 <= r < n.

A068934.name: Triangular array C(n, r) = number of connected r-regular graphs with n nodes, 0 <= r < n.
formula: Column k is the inverse Euler transform of column k of A051031. - _Andrew Howroyd_, Mar 10 2020

A068935.name: Numbers having the sum of distinct prime factors less than the sum of exponents in prime factorization, A008472(n) < A001222(n).

A068936.name: Numbers having the sum of distinct prime factors not greater than the sum of exponents in prime factorization, A008472(n)<=A001222(n).

A068937.name: Numbers having the sum of distinct prime factors not less than the sum of exponents in prime factorization, A008472(n)>=A001222(n).

A068938.name: Numbers having the sum of distinct prime factors greater than the sum of exponents in prime factorization, A008472(n)>A001222(n).

A068939.name: a(n) = Bell(n^2), where Bell(n) are the Bell numbers, cf. A000110.
formula: Integral representation as n-th moment of a positive function on a positive half-axis, in Maple notation: a(n)=int(x^n*(sum(exp(-ln(x)^2/ (4*ln(k)))/(k!*sqrt(ln(k))), k=2..infinity)/ (2*exp(1)*sqrt(Pi)*x) +Dirac(1-x)/exp(1)), x=0..infinity), n=0, 1, ...

A068940.name: Maximal number of chess queens that can be placed on a 3-dimensional chessboard of order n so that no two queens attack each other.

A068941.name: Maximum number of chess queens that can be placed on a 4-dimensional chessboard of order n so that no two attack each other.

A068942.name: a(n) = Bo(n^2), n=0,1..., where Bo(n) are the ordered Bell numbers, A000670.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k>=1} (k^(n^2))/2^(k+1); this is the analog of the Dobinski formula.

Integral representation as n-th moment of a positive function on a positive half-axis, in Maple notation: a(n)=int(x^n*(sum(exp(-ln(x)^2/(4*ln(k)))/(2^k*sqrt(ln(k))), k=2..infinity)/(4*sqrt(Pi)*x)+Dirac(x-1)/4), x=0..infinity), n=0, 1....

A068943.name: a(n) = f(n, n, n), where f is the generalized super falling factorial (see comments for definition.).

A068944.name: Highest power of 9 dividing A068943(n) for n>0.

A068945.name: Number of ones in the binary expansion of A068943(n).

A068951.name: Scan the primes, record digit-sum if it is itself prime.

A068953.name: Number of bases B (2 <= B <= n) such that every digit of n in base B is 0 or 1.

A068956.name: Number of distinct prime factors of n^n - (n-1)^(n-1).

A068957.name: Number of prime divisors of n^n - (n-1)^(n-1), counted with multiplicity.

A068958.name: Smallest value of k such that p | (10^k + 1), where p is the n-th prime; or 0 if no such k exists.

A068959.name: Decimal expansion of the smallest solution > Pi/2 to sin(x)=sin(x^2).

A068960.name: Decimal expansion of the fifth smallest positive real root of sin(x) - sin(x^3) = 0.
formula: Let x = (3*(45*Pi+sqrt(3*(4+675*Pi^2))))^(1/3) then the constant is (2^(1/3)*x^2-6)/(3*2^(2/3)*x). - _Peter Luschny_, Mar 12 2018

A068961.name: Powers of 2 with exactly two 2's in their decimal digits.

A068962.name: Number of successive terms of A028356 that add to n; or length of n-th term of A028355.
formula: Each group of 15 terms is 6 more than the previous group.

A068963.name: a(n) = Sum_{d|n} phi(d^3).
formula: Also Sum_{d|n} d*phi(d^2), or Sum_{d|n} d^2*phi(d).
Also Sum_{k=1..n} (n/gcd(n, k))^2 = Sum_{k=1..n} (lcm(n, k)/k)^2. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Dec 29 2002
G.f.: Sum_{k>=1} k^2*phi(k)*x^k/(1 - x^k). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Mar 10 2018
Dirichlet g.f.: Sum_{n>=1} a(n) / n^s = zeta(s) * zeta(s-3) / zeta(s-2). - _Werner Schulte_, Feb 18 2021

A068964.name: Numbers that define integer Heronian triangles [prime(a(n)), prime(a(n)+1), A068965(n)] with area A068966(n).

A068965.name: Sides of integer Heronian triangles [prime(A068964(n)), prime(A068964(n)+1), a(n)] with area A068966(n).

A068966.name: Areas of integer Heronian triangles [prime(A068964(n)), prime(A068964(n)+1), A068965(n)].

A068967.name: Numbers that define integer Heronian triangles [a(n), prime(a(n)), A068968(n)] with area A068969(n).

A068968.name: Sides of integer Heronian triangles [A068967(n), prime(A068967(n)), a(n)] with area A068969(n).

A068969.name: Areas of integer Heronian triangles [A068967(n), prime(A068967(n)), A068968(n)].

A068970.name: a(n) = Sum_{d|n} phi(d^4).
formula: G.f.: Sum_{k>=1} k^3*phi(k)*x^k/(1 - x^k). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Mar 10 2018

A068975.name: Composite n such that (n+1)*sum(d|n,d/sigma(d)) is an integer (1 excluded).

A068976.name: a(n) = Sum_{d | n} d/core(d) where core(x) is the smallest number such that x*core(x) is a square.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{d divides n} gcd(d, n/d)^2. Multiplicative with a(p^e) = (p^(e+2)+p^e-2)/(p^2-1) if e is even else 2*(p^(e+1)-1)/(p^2-1). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, May 30 2003
Dirichlet g.f.: zeta^2(s)*zeta(2s-2)/zeta(2s). Dirichlet convolution of A034444 and the sequence n*A010052(n). - _R. J. Mathar_, Apr 18 2011
Inverse Mobius transform of A008833. - _R. J. Mathar_, Oct 31 2011
a(n) = Sum_{d divides n} (-1)^A001222(d) * A000010(d) * A000203(n/d) = Sum_{k^2 divides n} k^2 * 2^A001221(n/k^2). - _Robert Israel_, Oct 18 2015

Sum_{k=1..n} a(k) ~ Zeta(3/2)^2 * n^(3/2) / (3*Zeta(3)) - (3*n*(log(n) - 1 + 2*gamma + 2*log(2*Pi) - 12*Zeta'(2)/Pi^2))/Pi^2, where gamma is the Euler-Mascheroni constant A001620. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Feb 05 2019

A068977.name: Numbers k such that Sum_{d|k} d/tau(d) is an integer, where tau(x)=A000005(x).

A068978.name: Numbers k such that Sum_{d|k} tau(d)/d is an integer, where tau(x) = A000005(x).

A068979.name: Number of elements of rank n in the free lattice on three generators.

A068980.name: Number of partitions of n into nonzero tetrahedral numbers.

A068982.name: Limit of the product of a modified Zeta function.

A068983.name: Sigma(k^k-k!).
formula: a(n) = sigma(k^k-k!) for k = 1 to n

A068985.name: Decimal expansion of 1/e.
formula: Equals j_1(i)/i = cos(i) + i*sin(i), where j_1(z) is the spherical Bessel function of the first kind and i is the imaginary unit in C. - _Stanislav Sykora_, Jan 11 2017
The series representation 1/e = Sum_{k >= 0} (-1)^k/k! is the case n = 0 of the following series acceleration formulas:
1/e = n!*Sum_{k >= 0} (-1)^k/(k!*R(n,k)*R(n,k+1)), n = 0,1,2,..., where R(n,x) = Sum_{k = 0..n} (-1)^k*binomial(n,k)*k!*binomial(-x,k) are the row polynomials of A094816. (End)
1/e = 1 - Sum_{n >= 0} n!/(A(n)*A(n+1)), where A(n) = A000522(n). - _Peter Bala_, Nov 13 2019
Equals Integral_{x=0..1} x * sinh(x) dx. - _Amiram Eldar_, Aug 14 2020

A068986.name: Numbers k such that Sum_{d|k} sigma(d)/d is an integer.

A068987.name: a(n) is the first position in the digit sequence 3,1,4,1,5,9,.... of Pi where the pattern "1,2,...,n" occurs (where position of the initial 3 is 1).

A068988.name: a(n) = first position in the decimal expansion of e where the pattern "1,2,...,n" occurs.

A068989.name: Squares which when reversed are primes (ignore leading zeros).

A068990.name: Primes which remain prime after each digit is increased by 2.

A068991.name: Numbers k such that Sum_{d divides k} sigma(d)/phi(d) is an integer.

A068992.name: Composite n such that sum(d|n, sigma(d)/tau(d)) is an integer (1 excluded).

A068994.name: Powers of 2 with all even digits.

A068995.name: Integer parts of the square roots of the schizophrenic numbers (A014824).

A068996.name: Decimal expansion of 1 - 1/e.
formula: Equals Integral_{x = 0 .. 1} exp(-x) dx. - _Alonso del Arte_, Jul 06 2012
Equals Integral_{x=0..1} x * cosh(x) dx. - _Amiram Eldar_, Aug 14 2020

A068997.name: Numbers n such that Sum_{d|n} d*mu(d) divides n.
formula: n such that A023900(n) divides n.

A068998.name: Numbers n such that the concatenation of the prime factors of n (in increasing order) is prime.

A068999.name: Numbers k such that k = (sum of distinct prime factors of k)*(product of distinct prime factors of k).

A069000.name: Numbers k such that k * (digit complement of k) is a square.
